UNIT 1 — LIFE ON EARTH

1. Ecosystems & Interdependence
Habitat: The place where an animal, plant or micro-organism lives.
Community: All the different species living in an area.
Population: The number of one species in an area.
Ecosystem: All the organisms living in a habitat and the non-living components they interact with.
Niche: The role an organism plays in its ecosystem.
Species: A group of organisms which can breed to produce fertile offspring.
Herbivore: An organism which eats only plant material.
Omnivore: An organism which eats both plant and animal material.
Carnivore: An organism which eats only animal material.
Producer: A green plant which produces its own food.

2. Competition & Environmental Factors
Biotic Factor: A living factor which can affect population size.
Abiotic Factor: A non-living factor which can affect population size.

3. Sampling Techniques
Quadrat: Tool to estimate plant numbers.
Pitfall Trap: Tool to estimate invertebrates.
Indicator Species: Species indicating environmental quality.

4. Photosynthesis
Photosynthesis: Process plants use to produce sugar.
Raw Materials: Carbon dioxide and water.
Products: Sugar and oxygen.
Conditions: Light energy and chlorophyll.
Light Reactions: Water split into hydrogen, oxygen, ATP.
Carbon Fixation: Hydrogen + CO2 + ATP → sugar.

UNIT 2 — CELL BIOLOGY

1. Cell Structure
Cell Membrane: Controls entry/exit of materials.
Cytoplasm: Site of chemical reactions.
Ribosome: Site of protein synthesis.
Nucleus: Contains genetic information.
Mitochondrion: Site of aerobic respiration.
Chloroplast: Site of photosynthesis.
Vacuole: Stores water and minerals.
Plasmid: Circular DNA in bacteria.

2. Transport
Diffusion: Movement from high to low concentration.
Osmosis: Movement of water through a selectively permeable membrane.
Active Transport: Movement against concentration gradient using energy.

3. DNA & Proteins
DNA: Double helix carrying genetic information.
Gene: Section of DNA coding for protein.
mRNA: Carries code to ribosome.
Protein: Chain of amino acids.

4. Enzymes
Enzyme: Protein speeding up reactions.
Substrate: Substance enzyme acts on.
Product: Substance produced.
Active Site: Region enzyme binds substrate.
Denatured: Enzyme shape changed and inactive.

UNIT 3 — MULTICELLULAR ORGANISMS

1. Cell Division
Chromosome: Thread-like genetic structure.
Chromatid: A chromosome and its copy.
Centromere: Joins chromatids.
Mitosis: Division producing identical cells.
Diploid: Two sets of chromosomes.
Haploid: One set of chromosomes.

2. Nervous System
CNS: Brain and spinal cord.
Sensory Neuron: Carries impulses to CNS.
Motor Neuron: Carries impulses from CNS.
Synapse: Gap between neurons.
Reflex: Automatic response.

3. Hormones
Hormone: Chemical messenger.
Insulin: Lowers blood glucose.
Glucagon: Raises blood glucose.

4. Reproduction & Inheritance
Gametes: Sex cells.
Zygote: Fertilised cell.
Variation: Differences between individuals.
Alleles: Different forms of a gene.
Genotype: Genetic makeup.
Phenotype: Physical traits.

5. Transport in Plants
Xylem: Carries water.
Phloem: Carries sugars.
Transpiration: Loss of water through leaves.

6. Circulatory System
Heart: Pumps blood.
Artery: Carries blood away.
Vein: Carries blood to heart.
Capillary: Site of diffusion.
Red Blood Cells: Carry oxygen.
White Blood Cells: Fight infection.

